helpdesk-ticket.subject: VPN Restriction
helpdesk-ticket.description: Hello, I am attempting to connect remotely to a company I work for through VPN. I know the VPN connection is operational when I'm on other networks, but the MSOE network seems to be blocking access to connect through to the remote network. Is this something that can be alleviated? I am able to provide connection information if needed. Thank you.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: Hello, I am attempting to connect remotely to a company I work for through VPN. I know the VPN connection is operational when I'm on other networks, but the MSOE network seems to be blocking access to connect through to the remote network. Is this something that can be alleviated? I am able to provide connection information if needed. Thank you.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi parksh,
I'm sorry. Unfortunately, VPNs are blocked on the network. To my understanding, this was done partially to crackdown on people using VPNs to get around the school's no piracy policy. I can elevate the ticket to Tier Three if you wish, but I don't believe this is something we can do. helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Cathlyn Ferraro, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5740
I am glad we were able to resolve your issue. I have included the instructions below to fix your printer problem.
1) Click the Windows Button in the bottom left 2) Select "Devices and Printers" 3) If you see a printer named "CC-370 Career Services" 4) Right Click the Printer named "CC-370 Career Services" 5) Select Remove Device 6) Click the Windows Button in the bottom left 7) Using the search box, search for and open "Run" 8) In the box that pops up, type \\printers.msoe.edu 9) In the windows that pops up, double click on the printer named "CC-370 Career Services"
This should reinstall the printer with the new settings.
Thanks,
Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

Rose
Rose Didier Administrative Assistant General Studies Department MSOE Phone: 414.277.7351 Fax: 414.277.7462 didier@msoe.edu
________________________________ From: Wikoff, Dr. Katherine Sent: Friday, February 19, 2016 2:34 PM To: Domack, Dr. Alicia; Didier, Rosemary Subject: RE: IT repair needed - GM 308 projector
I think Rose submitted the ticket, or will as soon as she can. I know she’s busy this week. But I can call Pat Hurlbut. Let’s assume IT will fix the problem. But if it looks like it’ll be an issue that continues into the upcoming quarter, I’ll let you know right away.
Thanks,
Katie
From: Domack, Dr. Alicia Sent: Friday, February 19, 2016 2:32 PM To: Wikoff, Dr. Katherine; Didier, Rosemary Subject: RE: IT repair needed - GM 308 projector
Have we submitted a ticket for this? You can also follow up with a call to Pat Hurlbut.
Alicia
From: Wikoff, Dr. Katherine Sent: Friday, February 19, 2016 2:28 PM To: Didier, Rosemary Cc: Domack, Dr. Alicia Subject: IT repair needed - GM 308 projector
Hi Rose,
I know I mentioned this to you the other day, but I thought I’d also send an email so I could copy Alicia with the related message.
The projector in GM 308 is not working right. Some connection appears to be loose. When my students presented on Wednesday, the color projected was usually off. For example, an orange slide projected as green. There seemed to be an overall bluish cast to the light when the slide background was white.
Right now I’m scheduled to teach a section of HU 489 Film Studies in GM 308 next term, but that room won’t be suitable if the projector isn’t repaired.
Alicia, I’m copying you on this message as a heads-up in case IT can’t fix GM 308 right away. I just checked the audio and video quality of GM 206, and the projector in that room is working well. If the GM 308 projector can’t be repaired by the first week of class, can we just ask Marc to switch my 1:00 HU 489 (Section 002) class from GM 308 to GM 206 instead?
I’m also going to stop in SS 341, my other HU 489 classroom (Section 001, 8:00am) next week to make sure that system is in good working order. I don’t expect problems, but since GM 308 is on the fritz, I just want to make sure everything is set over in the Science Building for the first day of class next quarter.
Thanks,
Katie
Katherine Wikoff, Ph.D.
Professor, General Studies Department
(414) 277-4542
wikoff@msoe.edu<mailto:wikoff@msoe.edu>
[MSOE]<https://www.msoe.edu/>

helpdesk-ticket.subject: blackboard sideways scroll
helpdesk-ticket.description:
I’m seeing something odd with Blackboard on a Mac: when I view the full grade center, there is no horizontal scroll bar. This is new – I only noticed this behavior today, and I think I would have noticed it last week. This happens with both Safari 9.0.3 and Chrome 48.0.2564. These are the current versions of both. I also did a fresh install of Firefox, and the horizontal scroll bar was missing there as well. I did confirm the horizontal scroll works for me on a Windows 10 system (actually, a VM on my Macbook). It seems Bb has new problems on Macs.
Rob
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
I’m seeing something odd with Blackboard on a Mac: when I view the full grade center, there is no horizontal scroll bar. This is new – I only noticed this behavior today, and I think I would have noticed it last week. This happens with both Safari 9.0.3 and Chrome 48.0.2564. These are the current versions of both. I also did a fresh install of Firefox, and the horizontal scroll bar was missing there as well. I did confirm the horizontal scroll works for me on a Windows 10 system (actually, a VM on my Macbook). It seems Bb has new problems on Macs.

Rob

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Rob Hasker,
The horizontal scroll bars on Macs disappear when not in use. You should be able to scroll with two fingers on the track pad in the horizontal direction.
Alternatively, you can set it up to always enable the scroll bar in horizontal direction through this walk though:
https://blog.richmond.edu/blackboard/2013/10/03/mac-os-x-missing-grade-center-scroll-bars/
Please let us know if this helps, or if you need any further assistance.
-Brad Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5765

helpdesk-note.body:
Pat was provided with the information for the new faculty member to create an account, as he had yet to do so.
The instructions provided were:
I looked for your account in the administrative tool and it appears it was not created. In order to create an account on the MSOE Community, please follow these steps:
1. Go to community.msoe.edu 2. Click on REGISTER in the upper portion of the screen. 3. Choose “I have MSOE credentials” 4. Complete the form with your MSOE email and password. 5. Click SUBMIT 6. You will receive an activation link. Please click on that activation link to create your account. 7. The link will redirect you back to the site and from there you can complete your profile.
Pat confirmed that she received the information and was going to walk through it with the new faculty member. If you do not receive the email, please check your SPAM filter. If you have followed the steps above and are still having issues, please let us know. You may also want to try to clear your cache, as depending on your browser, it may be saving an old version of the site.
If you have further questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact us at community@msoe.edu. ��0(�D7
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Pat was provided with the information for the new faculty member to create an account, as he had yet to do so.

The instructions provided were:

I looked for your account in the administrative tool and it appears it was not created. In order to create an account on the MSOE Community, please follow these steps:
 
1. Go to community.msoe.edu
2. Click on REGISTER in the upper portion of the screen.
3. Choose “I have MSOE credentials”
4. Complete the form with your MSOE email and password.
5. Click SUBMIT
6. You will receive an activation link. Please click on that activation link to create your account.
7. The link will redirect you back to the site and from there you can complete your profile.
 
 Pat confirmed that she received the information and was going to walk through it with the new faculty member.
If you do not receive the email, please check your SPAM filter. If you have followed the steps above and are still having issues, please let us know. You may also want to try to clear your cache, as depending on your browser, it may be saving an old version of the site.
 
If you have further questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact us at community@msoe.edu.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Hard Drive at the Helpdesk
helpdesk-ticket.description: Student's windows will not boot. I got him into a loaner hard drive temporarily so he can take his exam at 10. He has an 8560w, the HDD doesn't seem to be failing or anything, just windows corrupted. User will be back after his final to get remaining files on the Hard drive that is sitting near the left Helpdesk computer with his name on it.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: Student's windows will not boot. I got him into a loaner hard drive temporarily so he can take his exam at 10. He has an 8560w, the HDD doesn't seem to be failing or anything, just windows corrupted. User will be back after his final to get remaining files on the Hard drive that is sitting near the left Helpdesk computer with his name on it.

helpdesk-note.body: Full disclosure: I had to give him a HDD that belonged to someone else (in the past, it currently was unassigned but had not been stock processed apparently, because he had a final in 15 mins) because there was not a single bootable hard drive for a 60 or 70 in the cabinet. Why in the world was there not a single fresh image? Anyways, when user comes back please help him back up the stuff on his HDD, then image it at user's convenience, then take back the other HDD and do a stock process. This was disappointing. There may be working 60s and 70s, but the vast majority of them were in no condition to hand out, even as loaners.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Laptop Power-On Failure
helpdesk-ticket.description: laptop will not power on, no power indicator
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: laptop will not power on, no power indicator

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Kimberly Benson, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5862
One thing you can try to solve this problem is a hard reset. In order to perform this, remove the battery and the power cord from your computer. Once this is done, hold the power button for about 30 seconds. Finally, plug your charger back in and attempt to boot the computer.
If this doesn't work, I highly recommend bringing your computer into the helpdesk. From there we can decide if it is an easy fix or we will need to provide you a new unit. Let me know if this works,
Alexander Schroeder IT Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Kimberly Benson,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5862

One thing you can try to solve this problem is a hard reset.  In order to perform this, remove the battery and the power cord from your computer.  Once this is done, hold the power button for about 30 seconds.  Finally, plug your charger back in and attempt to boot the computer.

If this doesn't work, I highly recommend bringing your computer into the helpdesk.  From there we can decide if it is an easy fix or we will need to provide you a new unit.
Let me know if this works,


Alexander Schroeder
IT Helpdesk Technician
helpdesk@msoe.edu
414 277 7288

Alexander Schroeder IT Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu<mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu> 414 277 7288 On Tue, 16 Feb at 9:22 am , helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu<mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu>> wrote: Hi Lawrence Skuse,
To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus.
First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time. Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once!
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu
For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following. 1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”. 2. Open Credential Manager. 3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials” 4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…” 5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt. 6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook. 7. Outlook will ask you for your new password. 8. Outlook will start updating.
The password to log in to your laptop may remain the same as it was before you changed it. We can see, you recently changed your password at 2/16/2016 1:29 AM (CST) Please feel free to reply to this email if you have any concerns or questions.
Thanks Rishabh Gupta Help Desk Technician 414-277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu<mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu>

On Tue, 16 Feb at 9:22 am , helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu> wrote:
Hi Lawrence Skuse,

To change your password you need to open the following two links. These links will work on campus and off campus.

First, please register yourself through https://pwdreg.msoe.edu
This page will ask you to fill some security questions, which will allow us to recognize you without your password, at any time.
Because this is a failsafe, you should probably do this before your password troubles you again. You only need to do this once! 
 
You can then reset your password by visiting https://pwd.msoe.edu

For your Outlook to work, you need to do the following.
1. Open Start Menu, and search for “Credential Manager”.
2. Open Credential Manager.
3. You should see an option saying “Generic Credentials”
4. Under generic credentials, there should be an option saying “MSOutlook15…”
5. Click on that and press “Remove from Vault” and hit yes to the prompt.
6. Close credential manger and re-open outlook.
7. Outlook will ask you for your new password.
8. Outlook will start updating.

The password to log in to your laptop may remain the same as it was before you changed it. We can see, you recently changed your password at 2/16/2016 1:29 AM (CST)
Please feel free to reply to this email if you have any concerns or questions.

Thanks
Rishabh Gupta
Help Desk Technician
414-277-7288
helpdesk@msoe.edu

Greetings!
Welcome to another exciting edition of "Adventures in IP Phones!" In this ongoing series, Andy Holmes, Instructional Technologist, under the production of Ben Harris, Director of Desktop Management, will give you helpful tips to use your MSOE office phone. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Printing Poster
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello! For one of my graduate classes, we are required to create a poster (the same size as the senior design posters) for a conference we are attending in April. Can you please tell me the size of the paper, where we can get them printed (there will be five posters), and if you recommend designing the poster in PowerPoint or Publisher? I will then communicate that information to my instructor and to the other four students.
Thanks so much, Megan Justman
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello!
For one of my graduate classes, we are required to create a poster (the same size as the senior design posters) for a conference we are attending in April. Can you please tell me the size of the paper, where we can get them printed (there will be five posters), and if you recommend designing the poster in PowerPoint or Publisher? I will then communicate that information to my instructor and to the other four students.
 
Thanks so much,
Megan Justman

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Megan, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/5925
Our plotter can print a maximum of 36" in one direction and however long you need in the other. In order to print, we have to have the file in either a PDF or PowerPoint format. In order to print, put the file on a flash drive and bring it to the helpdesk and we will print it then. Are there any other questions I can answer for you? Alexander Schroeder IT Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288
helpdesk-note.body-html:

helpdesk-ticket.description:
To whom it may concern,
I recently graduated, and (seeing as I have not received any information about this yet) I have a few specific questions about the laptop policy:
· Is there a date by which I must bring in my laptop for finalization work?
· What is the nature of the work to be done? (e.g. is it a full wipe, selective, …)
· What software will be left on the device? Windows? Microsoft Office? …?
Thanks, Sean MacAvaney

Please let us know if you have further questions, Have a great day

helpdesk-note.body:
To further answer your questions: Is there a date by which I must bring in my laptop for finalization work? As soon as possible. A non-refundable late fee will be applied at 30 days.
· What is the nature of the work to be done? (e.g. is it a full wipe, selective, …) It is a full wipe. We apply the original Out-Of-Box image supplied by HP.
· What software will be left on the device? Windows? Microsoft Office? …?
It will just be Windows. With this information, I will mark this incident as resolved. Do not hesitate to contact the Help Desk with any additional questions. Congratulations Sean.
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202
helpdesk-note.body-html:

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Schenstrom,
That looks like a legitimate email from Google. When I receive anything suspicious I do some independent trouble shooting, never clicking any links in the email. Google recommends:
Check for suspicious account activity If you’ve received this email, we recommend you review your recent activity:
Go to your Recent Activity page. You may be asked to sign in to your account. Review your recent activity and look for unfamiliar locations or devices. You can also click on any event in the list to see more details about it on the right. If you see activity you don’t recognize, click Change password at the top of the page. Follow the steps to change your password.
It looks like they were unsuccessful in gaining access and Google is letting you know. Changing your password for your gmail account is the best defense and I would recommend it. Consider changing your MSOE password as well. It is good to know when something like this happens. Since they were unsuccessful, especially if you get no further notices, it could be something accidental rather than malicious.
I am going to mark this incident as resolved with this information. Thank you for bringing this to our attention and we are here to help whenever this happens again.
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202

helpdesk-note.body:
Prof. Schenstrom.
I am sorry I misread your initial report. Since you do not have a Google account, this is a phishing attempt to steal your password for your MSOE account. Do not click any links in the email and delete the email. Like all phishing attempts, if you do not click the links, you are safe. It is by clicking the links and "logging in" that your account gets compromised. In either case, clicking or not clicking, changing your password is the best defense. In terms of how to deal with the uncertainty of these types of attacks I offer this advice:
Never click a link that some unknown has sent to you, legitimate or not.
If I get any email with a link, I will open a browser and type it in manually. The MSOE IT department sends email notifications when your password is going to expire. This email has two links to help you. Even though I sent the email, I do not click the links, I open a browser and type them in. Building the habit of not clicking links. There is no way to be sure if the links are for real. If you do this one thing, not clicking links, you circumvent the bad guys attempts to steal your information. Another scenario is a popup that says something like "Your Java is out of date, click here to update" I never click that link, I will open a browser and go to Java.com and update my Java. You can substitute Adobe or Microsoft or any other major IT company that everyone uses for Java in my example. I never click the link, I go check myself.
If you have clicked the links and typed in your username and password, you MUST change your password right away. The MSOE IT department strongly recommends wiping your computer and starting fresh in this case as well. It is very hard to tell if a key logger or other form of malicious software was installed.
I also have sent this example to our Network Security Team so they are also aware of this phishing attempt.
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202

helpdesk-ticket.subject: OpenHAB Web Interface Problem
helpdesk-ticket.description: I’m having problems getting the OpenHAB (a home automation software package) web interface to work on my MSOE laptop. Here is summary of I’ve done and what is not working: I carefully followed online OpenHAB installation instructions (at http://www.openhab.org/getting-started). This involved downloading and installing the Runtime core (1.8) and Addons as well as their demo and the Habmin administration tool. I launched the runtime by executing the script start.bat. OpenHAB appears to run and a series of log type messages appear in the command window. These messages don’t indicate any errors and continue to update periodically as I think they should. However, OpenHAB is supposed to present a web interface at http://<openHAB address or hostname>:8080/openhab.app?sitemap=demo which I assumed would correspond to http://localhost:8080/openhab.app?sitemap=demo on my machine once I activated IIS7, which I did as follows. I activated IIS7 (localhost http access) using Control Panel > Programs and Features > Turn Windows features on or off. I then searched for Internet Information Services and checked its checkbox. I read online that by default IIS uses the contents of C:/inetpub/wwwroot for http://localhost and confirmed that the content of this folder is in fact displayed when I enter the address into my Chrome address field. However, accessing the localhost:8080 port using the URL listed above does not work. I keep getting 404 errors. I also tried downloading and installing habmin (https://github.com/cdjackson/HABmin) from https://github.com/cdjackson/HABmin/releases. It appears I’ll need it later to configure my z-wave network. Its interface is supposed to be presented at http://localhost:8080/habmin/index.html, but it doesn’t to work either. I suspect my firewall and/or windows security settings may be blocking access to the web interface port. Do you have any comments or suggestions? I plan to be on campus Friday and can bring my laptop to the helpdesk then. Note that I’ve also contacted some SE and CE faculty member and will be working with them in parallel. Charles

helpdesk-note.body:
Merged from ticket 6008 Subject: OpenHAB Web Access Issues Description: This message is a follow up to one I sent earlier today and is in direct response to a message I got on my MSOE voice mail from James.
James raised the issue of my problem being related to VPN/torrent blocking by MSOE. I suppose this is possible, if such blocking blocks all traffic on port 8080. However, what I’m trying to do does not directly involve BPN or torrents. The OpenHAB software simply presents its main UI as a web page on port 8080. It is normally run on a free standing machine that users access over the internet via any webkit based browser. There should be no need for VPN.
What I’m trying to do, is to run it on my MSOE laptop and also access its UI using a browser running on my laptop. As I understand it, this should be possible using localhost as the URL for the connection. However, I’m far from expert in this area, so I really don’t know what is possible.
Dr. Tritt

helpdesk-ticket.subject: MSOE password failures
helpdesk-ticket.description:
I’ve been locked out of my account at least once each day over the past three days. Each time the failure makes no sense: it’s not a case of me mistyping my password three times in a row, and it’s not a case of some device trying to use an old version of the password. If I wait half an hour to an hour, the problem fixes itself and I’m able to resume using my password. But this is definitely keeping me from getting important work done such as completing program assessments by deadlines. I’m suspicious Box is doing something odd that is being interpreted as a failed login attempt, but that is based on just the fact that I’ve been using Box more frequently over the past few days.
I would like to know what is causing the failures so I can either fix the problem at my end or it can be fixed in the authentication system. I would also propose that the 3 strike lockout policy be revisited: that policy made sense when people had a single login on a single machine, but people now have hundreds of logins and the chances of mistyping a password has gone up. At the same time, tighter restrictions on passwords has also meant that the chances of guessing a correct password have gone down significantly. It may be time to at least increase the number of failed attempts before lockout to (say at least) 10.
To help diagnose the problem, the most recent lockout occurred at about 11:15 a.m. this morning and I was able to reconnect at 11:38 a.m.
Rob Hasker EECS

I’ve been locked out of my account at least once each day over the past three days. Each time the failure makes no sense: it’s not a case of me mistyping my password three times in a row, and it’s not a case of some device trying to use an old version of the password. If I wait half an hour to an hour, the problem fixes itself and I’m able to resume using my password. But this is definitely keeping me from getting important work done such as completing program assessments by deadlines. I’m suspicious Box is doing something odd that is being interpreted as a failed login attempt, but that is based on just the fact that I’ve been using Box more frequently over the past few days. 

I would like to know what is causing the failures so I can either fix the problem at my end or it can be fixed in the authentication system. At the same time, tighter restrictions on passwords has also meant that the chances of guessing a correct password have gone down significantly. It may be time to at least increase the number of failed attempts before lockout to (say at least) 10.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi gagliano, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6006
This error occurs when the laptop is not on the school network only. If you are using the guest network the laptop may not verify with our licensing server. To fix this, simply connect to the school network via wired or wireless and the next time the message pops up, click the fix or verify button and it should find our servers.
If this does not fix the issue, there is no need to worry. Our machines will retain full functionality, with the occasional pop up. If this is not solved however, we can send a representative over to your office when we can. If this is the case, a few times in the next couple of business days that someone is available to show our representative the computer would be appreciated.
Thank you and have a nice day.
James Windorff Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288
